{{Use Australian English|date=May 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}} {{Infobox waterfall | name = Dinner Falls | photo = Queensland State Archives 1315 Rays Falls head of Barron River at Mount Hypipamee near Herberton c 1935.png | photo_width = 250px | photo_caption = Dinner Falls, at Mount Hypipamee near {{QLDcity|Herberton}}, ''circa'' 1935. | map = Queensland | relief = yes | map_width = 250px | coords_ref = <ref>{{Gazetteer of Australia|id=QLD10150|name=Dinner Falls (QLD)}}</ref><ref>{{cite QPN|10150|Dinner Falls|accessdate=13 September 2015}}</ref> | location = [[Far North Queensland|Far North]] [[Queensland]], [[Australia]] | coords = {{coord|17|25|59|S|145|29|00|E|type:waterbody_region:AU-QLD_scale:50000|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | elevation = | type = {{unordered list|[[Waterfall#Types|Plunge]]|[[Waterfall#Types|Segmented]]|[[Waterfall#Types|Cascade]]}} | height = | width = | height_longest = | average_width = | number_drops = 3 | average_flow = | watercourse = [[Barron River (Queensland)|Barron River]] | world_rank = }} The '''Dinner Falls''' is a mix of three [[waterfall]]s that display [[Waterfall#Types|plunge]], [[Waterfall#Types|segmented]] and [[Waterfall#Types|cascade]] characteristics on the upper [[Barron River (Queensland)|Barron River]] located in the [[Far North Queensland|Far North]] region of [[Queensland]], [[Australia]].
==Location and features== The waterfall is located approximately {{convert|25|km}} south of [[Atherton, Queensland|Atherton]] on the [[Atherton Tableland]] near the [[Mount Hypipamee Crater]] in the [[Mount Hypipamee National Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wettropics.gov.au/ttd/trackdtl?idtrack=54 |title=Things to Do Dinner Falls Circuit |accessdate=7 August 2009 |date= |work= |publisher=Wet Tropics Management Authority |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110226222244/http://wettropics.gov.au/ttd/trackdtl?idtrack=54 |archivedate=26 February 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> The bottommost of the waterfall series is a long cascade fall; the middle section of the falls is a trio of segmented drops; while the uppermost section of the falls has a triangular shape as it plunges off the tableland plateau.<ref name=wow>{{cite web|url=http://www.world-of-waterfalls.com/australia-dinner-falls.html|title=Dinner Falls|work=World of Waterfalls|publisher=Johnny T. Cheng|date=18 May 2008|accessdate=20 May 2014}}</ref>
Access to the falls is via a walking track.
