{{For|the Norse god|Höðr}}
[[File:Stein 1861 Africa Umars Jihad State.jpg|thumb|300px|An 1861 German map displaying unoccupied El Hodh amid the [[Toucouleur Empire]] of [[El Hadj Umar Tall|Umar Tall]].]]
'''Hodh''' or {{nowrap|'''El Hodh'''}}{{refn|Also encountered as '''Hōdh''', '''Ḥawḍ''',<ref>Fāsī, Muḥammad &&nbsp;al. [https://books.google.com/books?id=tw0Q0tg0QLoC&pg=PA130 ''General History of Africa'', Vol.&nbsp;III: ''Africa from the Seventh to the Eleventh Century'', p.&nbsp;130]. {{sc|unesco}} (Paris), 1988. Accessed 18&nbsp;Apr 2014.</ref> '''Hódh''',<ref name=hbm/> and '''al-Hodh'''.<ref>Ould-Mey, Mohameden. [https://books.google.com/books?id=iWxZ9JV-UOEC&pg=PA66 ''Global Restructuring and Peripheral States: The Carrot and the Stick in Mauritania'', p.&nbsp;66.] Rowman & Littlefield ([[Lanham, Massachusetts|Lanham]]), 1996. Accessed 18&nbsp;Apr 2014.</ref>}} (from the [[Arabic language|Arabic]] for "the [[Depression (geology)|Basin]]") is a region of [[West Africa]].<ref name=hbm>[[Henry Barth|Barth, Henry]]. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=bQobAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA712 ''Travels and Discoveries in North and Central Africa, being a Journal of an Expedition undertaken under the Auspices of H.B.M.'s Government, in the Years 1849&ndash;1855'', Vol.&nbsp;3, pp.&nbsp;712&nbsp;ff.] Harper & Bros. (New York), 1859. Accessed 18&nbsp;Apr 2014.</ref> Previously administered as part of [[French Sudan]] (present-day [[Mali]]), the area was transferred to [[French Mauritania]] in 1944, apparently on a whim of the colonial governor [[Laigret]].<ref>Lalonde, Suzanne. [https://books.google.com/books?id=x7qEqVpq9poC&pg=PA109 ''Determining Boundaries in a Conflicted World: The Role of'' Uti Possidetis, p.&nbsp;109.] McGill-Queen's University Press (Montreal), 2002. Accessed 18&nbsp;Apr 2014.</ref> The transfer was still resented upon Mali's independence.<ref>Touval, Saadia. [https://books.google.com/books?id=jP1cfD-VQRgC&pg=PA247 ''The Boundary Politics of Independent Africa'', p.&nbsp;247]. iUniverse, 1999. {{ISBN|1583484221}}. Accessed 18&nbsp;Apr 2014.</ref> Formerly more fertile, it is now largely a barren waste.<ref>Morgan, William &&nbsp;al. ''West Africa'', pp.&nbsp;254&nbsp;ff. Methuen, 1973.</ref>

It gave its name to the modern [[Mauritania]]n [[Regions of Mauritania|regions]] of [[Hodh Ech Chargui Region|Hodh Ech Chargui]] and [[Hodh El Gharbi Region|Hodh El Gharbi]].

