==Caucasus Mountains== [[Image:Mount Elbrus May 2008.jpg|thumb|right|[[Mount Elbrus]], [[Russia]]]] {| class="wikitable sortable" !No !Peak !Country !Elevation (m) !Prominence (m) !Col (m) |- |1 |[[Mount Elbrus]] |{{RUS}} |5,642 |'''4,741''' |901 |- |2 |[[Mount Bazarduzu]] |{{RUS}}&nbsp;/&nbsp;{{AZE}} |4,466 |'''2,454''' |2012 |- |3 |[[Mount Kazbek]] |{{RUS}}&nbsp;/&nbsp;{{GEO}} |5,034 |'''2,353''' |2681 |- |4 |[[Tebulosmta]] |{{RUS}}&nbsp;/&nbsp;{{GEO}} |4,493 |'''2,145''' |2348 |- |5 |[[Mount Aragats]] |{{ARM}} |4,090 |'''2,143''' |1947 |- |6 |[[Dykh-Tau]] |{{RUS}} |5,205 |'''2,002''' |3203 |- |7 |[[Dyultydag]] |{{RUS}} |4,127 |'''1,834''' |2293 |- |8 |[[Kapudzhukh Lerr]] |{{ARM}}&nbsp;/&nbsp;{{AZE}} |3,905 |'''1,820''' |2085 |- |9 |[[Gora Addala Shukgelmezr]] |{{RUS}} |4,152 |'''1,792''' |2360 |- |10 |[[Gora Shan]] |{{RUS}}&nbsp;/&nbsp;{{GEO}} |4,451 |'''1,775''' |2676 |- |} Two of these peaks (Mount Aragats and Kapudzhukh Lerr) are on the Asian side of the ridge of the Greater Caucasus, which forms the usual boundary between Europe and Asia , and four more are on the border itself and so in both Europe and Asia.
