''[[Bridge of Spies (film)|Bridge of Spies]]'' is a 2015 [[Historical period drama|historical]] [[legal thriller]] directed by [[Steven Spielberg]]. The screenplay was written by [[Matt Charman]] and [[Coen brothers|Joel and Ethan Coen]]. The film is set during the [[Cold War]] and is based on the [[1960 U-2 incident]] and its aftermath. [[Tom Hanks]] plays lawyer [[James B. Donovan]] who is tasked with negotiating the release of the captured American pilot [[Francis Gary Powers]] ([[Austin Stowell]]) in exchange for the convicted [[KGB]] spy [[Rudolf Abel]] ([[Mark Rylance]]). [[Alan Alda]], [[Sebastian Koch]], and [[Amy Ryan]] feature in supporting roles.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/reviews/bridge-of-spies-film-review-1201609677/|title=Film Review: 'Bridge of Spies'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=October 4, 2015|accessdate=June 30, 2016|last=Debruge|first=Peter}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/oct/05/bridge-of-spies-film-review-tom-hanks-steven-spielberg-cold-war-gary-powers-u2|title=Bridge of Spies review&nbsp;– Tom Hanks and Mark Rylance red hot in Steven Spielberg's magnificent cold war thriller|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=October 5, 2015|accessdate=June 30, 2016|last=Bradshaw|first=Peter}}</ref>

The film premiered at the [[2015 New York Film Festival|53rd New York Film Festival]] on October 4, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2015/scene/news/bridge-of-spies-premiere-new-york-film-festival-1201609971/|title='Bridge of Spies' Opens to a Standing Ovation at the New York Film Festival|work=Variety|date=October 4, 2015|accessdate=June 30, 2016|last=Cox|first=Gordon}}</ref> [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures]] gave the film a wide release on October 16 at over 2,800 theaters in the United States and Canada. ''Bridge of Spies'' grossed a worldwide total of over $165 million on a production budget of $40 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=coldwar2015.htm|title=Bridge of Spies|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=June 30, 2016}}</ref> [[Rotten Tomatoes]], a [[review aggregator]], surveyed 261 reviews and judged 91% to be positive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/bridge_of_spies/|title=Bridge of Spies (2015)|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=July 17, 2016}}</ref> The film garnered many awards and nominations in a variety of categories with particular praise for Rylance's performance.

''Bridge of Spies'' received six nominations at the [[88th Academy Awards]], including Best Picture, Best Original Screenplay, and Best Original Score. Rylance went on to win the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]].<ref name=Oscar/> At the [[69th British Academy Film Awards]], the film garnered nine nominations and won Best Supporting Actor for Rylance.<ref name=BAFTA/> He also won the Best Supporting Actor award from the [[AACTA Awards]], [[New York Film Critics Circle]], [[London Film Critics' Circle]], [[Toronto Film Critics Association]], and [[Vancouver Film Critics Circle]]. Rylance also received nominations at the [[Golden Globe Awards]] and the [[Screen Actors Guild Awards]]. Both the [[American Film Institute]] and the [[National Board of Review]] included ''Bridge of Spies'' in their top ten films of 2015.<ref name=AFI/><ref name=NBR/>

