[[Image:Piton de la Fournaise 1.JPG|thumb|right|250px|[[Piton de la Fournaise]], an active [[shield volcano]] formed by the Réunion hotspot]]
The '''Réunion hotspot''' is a [[volcanic]] [[hotspot (geology)|hotspot]] which currently lies under the island of [[Réunion]] in the [[Indian Ocean]]. The [[Chagos-Laccadive Ridge]] and the southern part of the [[Mascarene Plateau]] are volcanic traces of the Réunion hotspot.<ref name="Verzhbitsky">{{Cite journal|author=E. V. Verzhbitsky|title=Geothermal regime and genesis of the Ninety-East and Chagos-Laccadive ridges|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0264370702000686|journal=Journal of Geodynamics |volume=35 |year=2003|doi=10.1016/S0264-3707(02)00068-6|issue=3|pages=289|bibcode = 2003JGeo...35..289V }}</ref>
The hotspot is believed to have been active for over 65 million years. A huge eruption of this hotspot 65 million years ago is thought to have laid down the [[Deccan Traps]], a vast bed of [[basalt]] lava that covers part of central [[India]], and opened a rift which separated India from the [[Mascarene Plateau|Seychelles Plateau]]. The Deccan Traps eruption coincided roughly with the extinction of the [[dinosaur]]s, and there is considerable speculation that the two events were related. As the Indian plate drifted north, the hotspot continued to punch through the plate, creating a string of volcanic islands and undersea plateaux. The [[Laccadive Islands]], the [[Maldives]], and the [[Chagos Archipelago]] are [[atoll]]s resting on former volcanoes created 60–45 million years ago that subsequently submerged below sea level. About 45 million years ago the [[rift (geology)|mid-ocean rift]] crossed over the hotspot, and the hotspot passed under the [[African Plate]].
The hotspot appears to have been relatively quiet 45–10 million years ago, when activity resumed, creating the [[Mascarene Islands]], which include [[Mauritius]], [[Réunion]], and [[Rodrigues (island)|Rodrigues]]. Mauritius and Rodrigues Ridge were created 8–10 million years ago, and Rodrigues and Réunion Islands in the last two million years. [[Piton de la Fournaise]], a [[shield volcano]] on the southeastern corner of Réunion, is one of the most active volcanoes in the world, erupting last in August 2015.<ref name="Klemetti">{{Cite journal|author=Klemetti, Erik|year=2014|title=New Eruption at Piton de la Fournaise on Reunion Island|journal=Wired|url=https://www.wired.com/2014/06/new-eruption-at-piton-de-la-fournaise-on-reunion-island/|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6QWxgguM1|archivedate=22 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref>
